The Overall Question

The Question: How does the amount of weight a person wants to lose relate to their overall current health?

Why the question is important: If they are related, it suggests that some respondents are aware their health would improve if they reached their desired weight, but are unable to enact change. These people are interested in making a change, and so policies aimed at helping this group of people should be more effective than those focused on people who are more apathetic to change, or are less in need of larger lifestyle changes.

Why the answer is relevant: We can gain insights into how the habits of healthier individuals differ from those in poorer health, and use this to make recommendations on possible change. We can identify age and gender groups that effective policies should target, and factors that make these policies the most effective.

Team Plot and Conclusions

ggplot(cdc)+
  geom_density(aes(x=(wtdesire-weight),y=..density..,fill=genhlth),position="stack")+
  xlim(-75,25)+
  xlab("Desired Change in Weight (lbs)")+
  ylab("Percentage of Respondents")+
  scale_fill_discrete(name="General Health")+
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent)+ 
  ggtitle("Desired Weight Change")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

The answer: Just over 25% of respondents are happy at their current weight. As we move away from this value, we see that respondents in the categories of poor, fair, and good makeup the bulk of the proportion. These people represent those who would like to make a meaningful change in their overall health, but have been unable to do so thus far. This group should be targeted with policy decisions to maximize their effect.

Recommendations

People around 45-55 years old are most interested in losing weight, so policy changes should be tailored to this group when possible.

We found that people who are more engaged in improving their health, either through regular exercise or via doctor’s visits, were in general more motivated to make positive lifestyle changes. We recommend both:

  • Helping engage people who do not have healthcare with low cost alternatives.

  • Encouraging doctors to pursue all available avenues for aiding patients in losing weight.

We noticed a trend in the amount of people who worked out, what generel shape they were in, and the amount of weight they wanted to lose. We found that people who regularly work out only want minimal changes in their weight (<20) instead of large (20>) changes.

We also found that gender has little or no bearing on desired weight/gain or loss. Hence, policies meant to increase and improve health should not be tailored to just men or women. Outreach to both is necessary.

Individual Findings and Plots

Brian’s Plot

health_plan_label <- as_labeller(c(`0` = "No Health Plan", `1` = "Has a Health Plan"))
ggplot(cdc)+
  geom_boxplot(aes(x=genhlth,y=(wtdesire-weight)),outlier.alpha = .3,outlier.shape = 21,outlier.color = "red")+
  ylim(-175,125)+
  coord_flip()+
  facet_wrap(~hlthplan,labeller = health_plan_label)+
  ylab("Desired Change in Weight (lbs)")+
  xlab("General Health")

Individual Findings: At all general health levels, we find a larger number of outliers in the health plan group, compared to the no health plan group. Leading us to conclude that people who have a health plan generally want to change their weight more than those who don’t.

This suggests that people who are actively engaged in monitoring their health are better informed on what overall changes they need to make. Engaging the group with no health plan with low cost alternatives, such as health fairs, could help to inform them of what beneficial changes they can make.

Additionally, for those people with healthcare, encouraging doctors to refer patients to dieticians, when health plans allow, could help them to plot a path to their desired weight and health goals.

Andrew’s Plot

# Andrew's Plot
ggplot(data = cdc, mapping = aes(x = weight, y = wtdesire-weight))+
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm') +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = gender))+
  ylim(-200,100)+
  facet_grid(genhlth ~ exerany)

Individual Findings: This graph represents that there is a tendency that people who are of heavier weight and work out on the regular are usually unhappy with their current weight. The trend of the best fit line explains that people of poor health are more likely to be unhappy with their current weight and desire to lose weight. The majority of people no matter their general health usually prefer to gain a few pounds or stay at their current weight. Despite the status of their health, it seems the majority of people who workout only want minimal changes to their weight.

Clint’s plot

# Clint's Plot
ggplot(data = cdc) + geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = age, y = (wtdesire-weight), color = genhlth), se = FALSE) + facet_grid(genhlth~.) + xlim(15,90) + ylab("Desired Change in Weight") + scale_color_discrete(name = "Health Level")

Individual Findings: This graph is useful because it shows how the desired change in weight is greatest at around fifty years old, after which the desired change in weight decreases as individuals age. This graph also demonstrates visually how people who report their health as less than excellent had larger values for desired weight change providing evidence that people who percieve themselves to be in worse shape generally want to change their weight more. I would advise programs that target people in their middle ages (forty-five through fifty-five) for nutrician and weight loss programs to take advantage of the increased desire.

ggplot(data = cdc, mapping = aes(x = height, y = wtdesire-weight))+
  geom_hex()+
  xlim(50,80)+
  ylim(-50,50)+
  facet_wrap(~gender)

Individual Findings: This graph does a good job of demonstrating that there are high degrees of similarity for the health goals of Men and Women. Both Men and Women have a similar proportion of individuals seeking weight change of +/- 10 lbs, and the hex chart does well to show that the density of individuals seeking weight changes at particular heights are incredibly similar for men and women. The graph demonstrates that there is a higher density of men seeking to gain weight than women, though women also tend to want to gain weight and lose it. Thus, desired weight gain is similarly common in men and women as a desire to lose weight. I would advise that weight gain/loss and health programs target the broader audience of men and women and not simply advertise to one gender.
